<TITLE> Agencies train for earthquake relief </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Aug 10 (bdnews24.com)  A four-day long training course 'Durjog Durnibar-2008' to prepare for disaster operations, such as post-earthquake disaster management and humanitarian assistance, began Sunday, the Inter Service Public Relations Directorate said. The five-day joint-exercise would simulate disaster relief operations necessary following an earthquake. BIPSOT commandant inaugurated the exercises at the Bangladesh Institute of Peace Support Operation Training (BIPSOT), under the supervision of the Bangladesh Army and a US Marine Corps team, at Rajendrapur Cantonment in Gazipur. Bangladesh armed forces and other organisations have been given the responsibility to handle disaster operations in eight separate sectors under Dhaka City Corporation area, the statement said. The United States Marine Corps team based in Okinawa, Japan, is visiting Bangladesh to participate in the humanitarian assistance and disaster relief simulation exercise with the Bangladesh Armed Forces, said a USIS statement Sunday. Brigadier General Ronald Bailey, who commanded the US military forces that provided immediate humanitarian assistance following Cyclone Sidr, leads the US Marine Corps. The participants of the course include members of the Bangladesh Army, Bangladesh Rifles, Bangladesh Coast Guard, Bangladesh Police, Ansar, Village Defence Party, Bangladesh Fire Service and Civil Defence, Disaster Management Bureau, Bangladesh Red Crescent Society, USAID, DCC, Dhaka Water Supply and Sewerage Authority, Dhaka Electric Supply Company, Power Development Board, Roads and Highways Department, Titas Gas Transmission and Distribution Company Ltd, Health Directorate, Public Works Department, Bangladesh University of Engineering and Technology and the US Marine Forces. bdnew
